{"type":"message","id":"903379e6","parentId":"959d8aad","timestamp":"2026-02-15T14:50:11.639Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Reviewing Test Structure**\n\nI've confirmed that the cleanup phase completed successfully, clearing any errors. The `tests/` directory currently houses only the stress test executor script. Notably, `integration_sandbox.py` is absent, suggesting a different testing approach. I also located the `src/` directory, which should contain the primary code to be tested. Further, I found `dmarket_api.py` and `agent_wrapper.py`.\n\n\n**Focusing on Test Executor**\n\nI'm now diving into `tests/stress_test_executor.py` to understand its scope and whether it integrates with pytest. My current strategy hinges on either making this existing stress test pass or constructing a rudimentary integration test using available files like `dmarket_api.py`. The absence of `integration_sandbox.py` is a definite obstacle, but I must press forward with available resources.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771167011634_328","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"tests/stress_test_executor.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":7893,"output":299,"cacheRead":5388,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":8192,"cost":{"input":0.015785999999999998,"output":0.003588,"cacheRead":0.0010776000000000002,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0204516}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771167000919}}
{"type":"message","id":"adc8de10","parentId":"903379e6","timestamp":"2026-02-15T14:50:11.657Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771167011634_328","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import time\nimport json\nimport random\nimport string\nimport psutil\nimport threading\nimport logging\nimport os\nimport sys\nfrom concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor\n\n# Ensure logs directory exists\nos.makedirs(\"logs\", exist_ok=True)\n\n# Configure logging\nlogging.basicConfig(\n    filename=\"logs/stress_test_report.log\",\n    level=logging.INFO,\n    format=\"%(asctime)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s\"\n)\nconsole = logging.StreamHandler()\nconsole.setLevel(logging.INFO)\nlogging.getLogger().addHandler(console)\n\n# Configuration\nDURATION_SECONDS = 600  # 10 minutes\nTARGET_REQ_PER_SEC = 20\nWORKERS = 4\nPAYLOAD_SIZE_MB = 5\nDRY_RUN = True\n\n# Mock Classes\nclass MockTradeManager:\n    def process_item(self, item):\n        # Simulate processing logic: basic validation and math\n        if not isinstance(item, dict):\n            return\n        \n        price = float(item.get(\"price\", {}).get(\"USD\", 0)) / 100.0\n        title = item.get(\"title\", \"\")\n        \n        # CPU burn simulation (regex or string ops)\n        _ = title.lower()[::-1]\n        \n        if price < 5.0:\n            return \"buy\"\n        return \"pass\"\n\ntry:\n    import orjson\n    JSON_LIB = orjson\n    def json_dumps(obj):\n        return orjson.dumps(obj).decode('utf-8')\n    def json_loads(obj):\n        return orjson.loads(obj)\nexcept ImportError:\n    import json\n    JSON_LIB = json\n    json_dumps = json.dumps\n    json_loads = json.loads\n    logging.warning(\"orjson not found, falling back to standard json (slower).\")\n\ndef generate_large_payload(size_mb):\n    \"\"\"Generates a synthetic DMarket-like JSON response of approx size_mb.\"\"\"\n    item_template = {\n        \"itemId\": \"1234567890\",\n        \"type\": \"dmarket\",\n        \"amount\": 1,\n        \"classId\": \"123456\",\n        \"gameId\": \"a8db\",\n        \"inMarket\": True,\n        \"lockStatus\": False,\n        \"price\": {\"USD\": 1234, \"DMC\": 1200},\n        \"title\": \"AK-47 | Redline (Field-Tested)\",\n        \"description\": \"A very nice gun.\",\n        \"slug\": \"ak-47-redline-field-tested\",\n        \"owner\": \"0x1234567890abcdef\",\n        \"attributes\": [\n            {\"name\": \"float\", \"value\": \"0.1500001\"},\n            {\"name\": \"paintSeed\", \"value\": \"123\"}\n        ]\n    }\n    \n    # Estimate item size\n    sample_dump = json_dumps(item_template)\n    item_size = len(sample_dump)\n    \n    target_bytes = size_mb * 1024 * 1024\n    num_items = target_bytes // item_size\n    \n    items = []\n    for _ in range(int(num_items)):\n        # Randomize slightly to prevent perfect caching if any\n        itm = item_template.copy()\n        itm[\"itemId\"] = \"\".join(random.choices(string.digits, k=10))\n        itm[\"price\"][\"USD\"] = random.randint(100, 50000)\n        items.append(itm)\n        \n    return json_dumps({\"objects\": items})\n\ndef worker_task(payload, trade_manager, request_id):\n    start_time = time.time()\n    \n    # 1. Parse\n    try:\n        data = json_loads(payload)\n    except Exception as e:\n        logging.error(f\"Req {request_id}: JSON Parse Error: {e}\")\n        return\n        \n    parse_time = time.time()\n    \n    # 2. Process\n    items = data.get(\"objects\", [])\n    processed_count = 0\n    for item in items:\n        trade_manager.process_item(item)\n        processed_count += 1\n        \n    end_time = time.time()\n    \n    parse_latency = (parse_time - start_time) * 1000\n    total_latency = (end_time - start_time) * 1000\n    \n    # Log spikes\n    if total_latency > 100:\n        logging.warning(f\"Req {request_id}: High Latency! Total: {total_latency:.2f}ms (Parse: {parse_latency:.2f}ms) - Items: {processed_count}\")\n    \n    return processed_count, total_latency\n\ndef run_stress_test():\n    logging.info(f\"Starting Stress Test: {DURATION_SECONDS}s, {TARGET_REQ_PER_SEC} req/s, {PAYLOAD_SIZE_MB}MB payload\")\n    \n    process = psutil.Process()\n    trade_manager = MockTradeManager()\n    \n    # Pre-generate payload to avoid generating it during the measurement window\n    logging.info(\"Generating synthetic payload...\")\n    payload = generate_large_payload(PAYLOAD_SIZE_MB)\n    logging.info(f\"Payload generated. Size: {len(payload)/1024/1024:.2f} MB\")\n    \n    start_test_time = time.time()\n    req_counter = 0\n    \n    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=WORKERS) as executor:\n        while (time.time() - start_test_time) < DURATION_SECONDS:\n            loop_start = time.time()\n            \n            # Launch batch of requests\n            futures = []\n            for _ in range(TARGET_REQ_PER_SEC):\n                req_counter += 1\n                futures.append(executor.submit(worker_task, payload, trade_manager, req_counter))\n            \n            # Monitor Resources\n            mem_info = process.memory_info()\n            cpu_percent = process.cpu_percent(interval=None)\n            logging.info(f\"Stats: RAM: {mem_info.rss / 1024 / 1024:.2f} MB | CPU: {cpu_percent}% | Req: {req_counter}\")\n            \n            # Sleep to maintain rate\n            elapsed = time.time() - loop_start\n            sleep_time = max(0, 1.0 - elapsed)\n            time.sleep(sleep_time)\n\n    logging.info(\"Stress Test Completed.\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    run_stress_test()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771167011655}}
{"type":"message","id":"33eaec43","parentId":"adc8de10","timestamp":"2026-02-15T14:50:21.850Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Diagnosing the Problem**\n\nI'm zeroing in on the contradiction. The user's trying to run pytest on a directory, which suggests tests, but the main script isn't structured as a pytest test file. My next step will be to explore whether the `stress_test_executor.py` script is intended to be invoked by the tests themselves, or if something else is amiss in the configuration.\n\n\n**Re-Evaluating the Structure**\n\nI've got a clearer picture now. The core issue is the conflict between the standalone nature of the `stress_test_executor.py` script and the user's attempt to run `pytest`. The instructions highlight the need for HFT speed and I'm aware of the missing `orjson` import and the lack of a test suite. I intend to build a test suite to validate the logic within `stress_test_executor` and ensure `orjson` is used.\n\n\n**Mapping Out the Strategy**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the problem's intricacies. The key is to construct a practical and targeted test suite. I've pinpointed the essential steps: installing the required packages, and crafting a `test_hft_compliance.py` file to validate the core logic, ensuring `orjson` is in use. I will also generate `integration_sandbox.py` to examine the API integration points. Now, it's about diving into the codebase to gain context.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771167021845_329","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem -Path src -Recurse"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":9693,"output":561,"cacheRead":5702,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":10254,"cost":{"input":0.019386,"output":0.006732,"cacheRead":0.0011404000000000002,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.027258400000000002}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771167011657}}
